# ============================================================================
# ADAPT-INSURANCE — CURSOR RULES
# ============================================================================
# Project: AdaptInsure — AI-Powered Insurance Adapter Platform
# Stack: Python 3.12 | FastAPI | Gemini API | Pydantic v2 | Jinja2 | pytest
# Author: Bhargavi | Weekly Weights
# ============================================================================

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# EXECUTION PROTOCOL
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# You are a senior engineer building a production-grade platform.
#
# Before writing ANY code:
# 1. Read PROJECT.md to understand the full system
# 2. Read TASKS.md to know what phase you are on
# 3. Read the current phase spec (docs/PHASE_X_SPEC.md) — this is your scope
# 4. State what you are about to do and why
# 5. Plan the approach — list files you will touch and what changes
# 6. Wait for approval before writing code
#
# Rules:
# - One task at a time. Complete it, test it, commit it. Then move on.
# - Phase specs are the source of truth. Build what the spec says. Nothing more.
# - If the spec says don't build it, don't build it.
# - If something is ambiguous, ask. Don't guess.
# - If you break something, revert and redo. Don't patch on top of broken code.
# - Every function has a docstring. Every module has a module docstring.
# - No commented-out code in commits. Delete it or keep it.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# PYTHON STANDARDS
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# - Python 3.12. Use modern syntax (match/case, type unions with |, etc.)
# - Type hints on EVERY function signature. No exceptions.
# - Pydantic v2 for all data models. model_validator, field_validator.
# - Use pathlib.Path, not os.path.
# - Use f-strings, not .format() or %.
# - Use logging, not print. Configure once in config.py.
# - Use async/await for IO-bound operations (API calls, file reads).
# - Imports: stdlib first, third-party second, local third. Blank line between groups.
# - Functions under 50 lines. If longer, split.
# - Files under 300 lines. If longer, split.
# - No wildcard imports. No circular imports.
# - All amounts use Decimal, never float. Insurance requires precision.
# - All dates use datetime with timezone awareness (UTC).
# - Enums use StrEnum for JSON serialization.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# PYDANTIC RULES
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# - All models inherit from BaseModel with model_config = ConfigDict(strict=True)
# - Use Annotated types with Field() for descriptions and constraints
# - field_validator for single-field validation
# - model_validator(mode="after") for cross-field validation
# - All optional fields explicitly typed as T | None = None
# - No dict[str, Any] unless it's raw_data passthrough — type everything else

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FASTAPI RULES
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# - All endpoints prefixed with /api/v1/
# - Success (single): { "data": { ... } }
# - Success (list): { "data": [...] }
# - Error: { "detail": "Human-readable message" }
# - Proper HTTP status codes (201 for creation, 422 for validation, etc.)
# - Dependency injection for shared services
# - All request/response bodies are Pydantic models — no raw dicts

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# LLM INTEGRATION RULES
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# - All LLM calls go through a single client wrapper in src/llm/client.py (Google Gemini via google-genai)
# - Every LLM call has: system prompt, user prompt, expected output schema
# - Every LLM response is validated against a Pydantic model before use
# - If LLM output fails validation, retry once with error feedback, then raise
# - LLM calls are async
# - Log every LLM call: prompt hash, token count, latency, success/failure
# - Never let LLM write production code. LLM outputs configs. Templates write code.
# - Temperature 0.0 for schema mapping. Temperature 0.2 for edge case generation.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TEMPLATE / CODE GENERATION RULES
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# - Jinja2 templates live in src/generator/templates/
# - Templates produce valid Python that passes ruff and mypy
# - Generated code goes to generated/ directory
# - Generated code is never edited by hand — regenerate from config
# - Every generated adapter has a header comment: "AUTO-GENERATED — DO NOT EDIT"
# - Generated test files follow pytest conventions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TESTING RULES
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# - pytest for everything
# - tests/ directory mirrors src/ structure
# - Every public function has at least one test
# - Use fixtures in conftest.py for shared setup
# - Synthetic insurer data in samples/ — never hardcode test data in test files
# - Test names: test_<what>_<condition>_<expected>
#   Example: test_parse_guidewire_claim_returns_valid_profile
# - No mocking of core business logic. Mock only external calls (LLM API, file IO).

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ERROR HANDLING
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# - Custom exception hierarchy rooted in AdaptInsureError
# - Every exception has: error_code (str), message (str), details (dict | None)
# - Categories: SchemaValidationError, DiscoveryError, MappingError, GenerationError,
#   TestHarnessError, MonitorError, LLMError, ConfigError
# - Never catch bare Exception. Catch specific types.
# - Log errors with full context before re-raising.
# - API endpoints return structured error responses, never stack traces.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# GIT RULES
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# - Commit after EVERY working feature. Small, frequent commits.
# - Format: type(scope): short description
#
#   Types: feat, fix, refactor, test, docs, chore, schema
#   Scopes: schema, discovery, mapping, generator, testing, monitor, api, samples
#
#   Examples:
#     feat(schema): add Claim and Exposure pydantic models
#     feat(discovery): implement JSON parser with field type inference
#     test(mapping): add semantic matcher tests for guidewire fields
#     docs: write Phase 1 spec
#     fix(generator): handle nullable fields in adapter template
#     schema: add catastrophe_code to Claim model
#     chore: update requirements.txt
#
# - Work on main. No branch overhead for solo builds.
# - Never commit: .env, __pycache__, generated/*.py (except .gitkeep),
#   .DS_Store, *.pyc, .pytest_cache
# - Tag each completed phase: git tag -a phase-X-complete -m "Phase X done"
# - Commit message must describe WHAT changed, not HOW.
#   Bad:  "updated file"
#   Good: "feat(discovery): add XML namespace detection for ACORD formats"

